  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In this paper we prove the existence of solutions to the viscous, non-resistive magnetohydrodynamics (MHD) equations on the whole of <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></math> , <math altimg="si12.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>3</mn></math> , for divergence-free initial data in certain Besov spaces, namely <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">u</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>∈</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup></math> and <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>∈</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math> . The a priori estimates include the term <math altimg="si5.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msubsup><mrow><mo>∫</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></msubsup><msubsup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">‖</mo><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">u</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">‖</mo></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mspace width="0.2em"></mspace><mi mathvariant="normal">d</mi><mi>s</mi></math> on the right-hand side, which thus requires an auxiliary bound in <math altimg="si6.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> . In 2D, this is simply achieved using the standard energy inequality; but in 3D an auxiliary estimate in <math altimg="si7.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math> is required, which we prove using the splitting method of Calderón (1990) [2] . By contrast, our proof that such solutions are unique only applies to the 3D case.</subfield>
